<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="61.[699,1228,193,1448]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
DIAGNOSIS: This specimen is superficially very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="OPITZ, 2005" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1015,1143,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coactus" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[1015,1143,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">A. coactus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1165,1222,369,392]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, from which they may be separated by the lack of densely distributed white setae on the distal third of the elytra. Also, in 
<taxonomicName authority="OPITZ, 2005" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1108,1220,457,480]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="domus" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[1108,1220,457,480]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">A. domus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[699,755,486,509]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, specimens the female pygidium is not trigonal, which is the case in 
<taxonomicName authority="OPITZ, 2005" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1090,1220,516,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coactus" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[1090,1220,516,539]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">A. coactus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[699,755,545,568]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, specimens (compare figs. 95, 96).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="61.[699,1228,193,1448]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
DESCRIPTION: 
<emphasis box="[891,938,575,598]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Size</emphasis>
: Length 5.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[699,793,604,627]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[805,936,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Integument</emphasis>
: Black. 
<emphasis box="[1037,1142,604,627]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Vestiture</emphasis>
: Integument densely vested with prominent light and dark setae; elytral middiscal setal tuft comprised of two patches, anterior and posterior patches approximately equal in size. 
<emphasis box="[699,762,751,774]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Head</emphasis>
: Finely punctate; interocular depressions and frontal umbo moderately developed; eyes oval, moderately convex; width across eyes slightly narrower than width across pronotum (33:38); antenna (fig. 223) shorter than length of pronotum (30:40). 
<emphasis box="[699,783,927,950]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly longer than broad (40:38); disc finely punctate, subapical depression faintly visible, side margins moderately arcuate; elytra moderately convex, depth at humerus 20, greatest depth in posterior half 30; elytral middiscal setal patch as in figure 232. 
<emphasis box="[869,979,1103,1126]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Posterior margin of female pygidium evenly arcuate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[699,1228,193,1448]" box="[728,1015,1161,1184]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">VARIATION: Not studied.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="61.[699,1228,193,1448]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
NATURAL HISTORY: The available specimen was collected in June, by beating within a deciduous forest located at an altitude of 
